05031nam a22006615i 9781442675049DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181998onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426750497 a10.3138/97814426750492doi  a(DE-B1597)497176  a(OCoLC)1078916512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aE99.E7bB659813 1998eb 7aHIS0280002bisacsh04a917.19/504222100aFranz Boas among the Inuit of Baffin Island, 1883-1884 :bJournals and Letters /ced. by Ludger Muller-Wille. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface to the Original German Edition -- tPreface to the English Edition -- tIntroduction: Germans and Inuit on Baffin Island in the 1880s -- tAbbreviations -- tPeriod of Preparation in Germany, 1882-1883 -- tOn Board the Germania from Hamburg to Baffin Island, June -July 1883 -- tIn the Drift and Pack Ice off Baffin Island, July-August 1883 -- tWinding Down the German Polar Station, K'ingua, September 1883 -- tLate Fall Boat Trips in the Sound, September-October 1883 -- tInvestigations at K'exerten, October-December 1883 -- tInuit, Igloos, and Dogs: Journeys on the Ice of Tinixdjuarbing, December 1883 - May 1884 -- tOverland to Davis Strait: From Kingnait to Padli, May 1884 -- tAlong the East Coast of Baffin Island: Survey Trips on the Sea Ice, May-July 1884 -- tAt K'ivitung: Waiting for the Whalers, July-August 1884 -- tLeaving the Inuit and the Arctic, August-September 1884 -- tAppendix 1. Dog Names -- tAppendix 2. Names of Ships and Boats -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the summer of 1883, Franz Boas, widely regarded as one of the fathers of Inuit anthropology, sailed from Germany to Baffin Island to spend a year among the Inuit of Cumberland Sound. This was his introduction to the Arctic and to anthropological fieldwork. This book presents, for the first time, his letters and journal entries from the year that he spent among the Inuit, providing not only an insightful background to his numerous scientific articles about Inuit culture, but a comprehensive and engaging narrative as well.Using a Scottish whaling station as his base, Boas travelled widely with the Inuit, learning their language, living in their tents and snow houses, sharing their food, and experiencing their joys and sorrows. At the same time he was taking detailed notes and surveying and mapping the landscape and coastline. Ludger Müller-Wille has transcribed his journals and his letters to his parents and fiancé and woven these texts into a sequential narrative. The result is a fascinating study of one of the earliest and most successful examples of participatory observation among the Inuit. Originally published in German in 1994, the text has been translated into English by William Barr, who has also published translations of other important works on the history of the Arctic. Illustrated with some of Boas's own photos and with maps of his field area, Franz Boas among the Inuit of Baffin Island, 1883-1884 is a valuable addition to the historical and anthropological literature on southern Baffin Island.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInuitzNorthwest TerritorieszBaffin IslandxSocial life and customsy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh1 aBarr, William.1 aMuller-Wille, Ludger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267504940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97814426750